<TEXT>
japan is putting pressure on the bush 
administration to ease restrictions on log exports a newspaper 
reported tuesday 
according to the oregonian ryohei murata japanese ambassador 
to the united states wrote a letter to us trade representative 
carla a hills on june 15 asking the government to oppose tougher 
export restrictions 
the newspaper which obtained a copy of the letter said murata 
wrote that the restrictions seriously impede trade between the 
two countries 
we are especially concerned with the fact that there are 
active movements in the us congress to further strengthen log 
export restrictions murata wrote we strongly request that the 
us government take effective actions to oppose such legislation 
japan the biggest foreign buyer of us logs imported 47 
billion board feet of logs from the united states last year china 
imported about 17 billion board feet and south korea imported less 
than half that amount 
legislation is moving through congress that would make permanent 
the annual ban on exporting federal logs from the west except 
alaskan logs and ban log exports from most state lands 
the bush administration supported such measures june 19 in a 
statement about declining timber supplies and the listing of the 
northern spotted owl as a threatened species 
some proponents of a log export ban believe it would encourage 
overseas buyers to use us sawmills 
japans foreign ministry says the existing ban on exports of 
federal logs in the west violates the general agreement on tariffs 
and trade the international agreement governing most trade as 
would further restrictions us forest products industry leaders 
also oppose the legislation fearing losses to japanese sawmills 
hills said in a reply to murata that the administration had told 
congress of concerns about the effects of trade restrictions 
we will continue to seek to ensure that any actions taken in 
this area especially in the context of domestic conservation 
programs are to the maximum extent possible consistent with our 
international obligations hills said 
shotaro yachi economic counselor at the japanese embassy in 
washington called hills letter vague 
we wanted a strong commitment yachi said we have been 
importing logs from your country and wed like to continue 
japan has about 17500 sawmills which employ 131000 workers 
nishitani could not estimate the number of jobs that depend on us 
log imports 
japan imports logs dutyfree but levies tariffs on many 
processed wood products washington persuaded tokyo during the 
yearlong wood products talks to lower some tariffs to boost exports 
of finished lumber to japan 
</TEXT>
