<TEXT>
president bush is suggesting a change in 
natos nuclear doctrine that is a modest shift away from atomic 
brinkmanship analysts say but the cold war question remains when 
would the west use its deadly nuclear arms 
that question has confounded allied leaders for most of natos 
41year history 
the answer has never been clear but the issue is regaining a 
policy spotlight as the western allies try to overhaul the north 
atlantic treaty organization and adjust their defense strategies to 
political changes in eastern europe 
administration sources said monday that bush will propose at a 
nato summit thursday that alliance doctrine be revised to declare 
that nuclear arms are weapons of last resort 
such a statement if endorsed as official nato policy would be 
at least a small step away from the existing doctrine known as 
flexible response according to private analysts interviewed 
monday 
flexible response holds that us nuclear arms could be 
fired during the early stages of a european ground war started by 
soviet nonnuclear forces if nato troops were being overrun 
by calling us nuclear forces in europe weapons of last 
resort bush is suggesting the united states would wait longer to 
initiate a nuclear battle than it would under existing nato 
doctrine said john steinbruner director of foreign policy studies 
at the brookings institution a liberaloriented washington think 
tank 
its unclear how bush or the allies would define a last 
resort 
the weapons in question are called battlefield nuclear weapons 
because they cannot reach beyond central europe long considered 
the most likely war theater 
only if use of these weapons failed to end the conflict would 
the united states consider resorting to use of strategic or 
longrange nuclear weapons 
steinbruner said the use of the term last resort seemed to 
suggest the administration was contemplating only a moderate shift 
in nato doctrine since bush apparently would not rule out that 
nato could be the first to fire battlefield nuclear weapons 
theyre dancing rhetorically around the subject steinbruner 
said 
the topic is particularly touchy for nato governments because 
while the demise of the sovietled warsaw pact is making nuclear 
weapons less important in europe no member of the western alliance 
is yet willing to abandon nuclear defenses altogether 
the london nato summit is expected to launch a major review of 
nuclear strategy details of a revised military stance are unlikely 
to be worked out for months 
frank j gaffney director of the conservative center for 
security policy said he interpreted bushs proposal as an attempt 
to placate the soviet union which argues that the reunification of 
germany requires that nato drop its military role 
gaffney said bushs proposal would erode the credibility of 
nato since it would bring the alliance closer to renouncing all 
use of nuclear weapons in europe 
we are in the name of trying to alleviate soviet concerns 
going to accede to radical changes in the character of natos 
traditional security arrangement he said 
david shorr associate director of the british american security 
information council a private organization based in london and 
washington said bushs proposal amounts to a rhetorical device 
with little substantive meaning 
he said the proposal was unlikely to help resolve the issue 
within nato regarding when in a conventional war against the 
soviets the west would resort to nuclear weapons 
it shows what a delicate dance nato has had to do around 
exactly what flexible response means shorr said 
</TEXT>
