<TEXT>
this is a town that is drowning in words 
swimming in information but parched for facts when decisions have 
to be made the decisionmakers in congress in the white house 
in the agencies of government afloat in data and analysis still 
yearn for the decisive fact that will tell them what to do 
would reducing the tax on capital gains give the economy a 
booster shot as president bush claims or merely deepen the 
deficit gap as his democratic opponents say 
if the house ways and means committee were to announce hearings 
on that question today the corridors would be crowded tomorrow 
with experts carrying briefcases loaded with facts to prove 
indisputably both sides of the argument 
predictive facts what would happen if are not the only kind 
that are hard to come by so are contemporary facts homelessness 
is a gnawing social problem high in the public consciousness the 
subject of strenuous government effort yet no one knows how many 
homeless people are out there or who they are or how long they 
have been homeless 
back in 1971 president richard nixon concerned by inflation 
took the unprecedented step of imposing peacetime wage and price 
controls on the economy overnight it became illegal to raise the 
price of a buick or a bagel it was a radical move for a republican 
president intended to stem inflation that he saw as threatening to 
the economy and his reelection prospects 
and yet says herbert j stein who was one of nixons economic 
advisers there was a lot of uncertainty about what the rate of 
inflation actually was inflation was and is measured in dozens 
of ways and no one can say which measurement most accurately 
reflects the rise in the price of goods and services 
thats not all says stein we still dont know what caused 
the depression in 1929 theres still disagreement over whether 
some international thing was moving the whole world or whether it 
was the way the monetary system was being managed 
its hard to get information on a lot of subjects he says 
take all the talk on the sampl business it is hard to find where 
all the estimates of losses which seem to change monthly come 
from we have very little information about what happened in the 
first place 
when president franklin d roosevelt died in 1945 and vice 
president harry s truman suddenly became president he learned 
about the secret work on the atomic bomb and one of the first 
decisions he had to make was whether to use it against japan 
fleet adm william d leahy chief of staff to roosevelt came 
to him truman recalls in his memoirs and in absolute certainty 
advised him not to use the bomb 
that is the biggest fool thing we have ever done he 
observed in his sturdy salty manner truman writes the bomb 
will never go off and i speak as an expert in explosives 
thats the trouble with experts of which this town is also 
full their opinions always parade as facts 
says charles schultze who played the same role for president 
jimmy carter that stein played for nixon there are zillions of 
facts the question is having all those facts what do you 
conclude 
if you ask me what a reduction in capital gains taxation would 
do to federal revenues i can get you two highly quantitative 
reports full of numbers one saying it will go up and one saying 
it will go down sometimes the facts come from people who want 
them to be true 
as long ago as 1931 charles evans hughes then chief justice 
reflected in a speech on the potency of facts 
said hughes an unscrupulous administrator might be tempted to 
say let me find the facts for the people of my country and i 
care little who lays down the general principles 
says jim jaffe a savvy aide on capitol hill since 1976 look 
at whats happening behind what we used to call the iron curtain 
you can say one of two things you can say the reagan plan of 
spending like a madman figure theyd run out of money before we 
would has been wildly successful or you can say the communist 
world was deteriorating anyhow and look at all the domestic 
concerns we ignored while we were wasting all this money on 
missiles we had no need for its an intellectual game its 
not a factual game 
there are lots of facts in washington but judgment is always 
scarce thats a fact 
</TEXT>
