<TEXT>
if pilots on longhaul flights are allowed to 
take a brief snooze in the cockpit theyre more alert for the 
landing a federal study concludes 
the national aeronautics and space administration study of 10 
boeing 747 crews produced the first scientific evidence that short 
rest periods act as a safety valve to reduce fatigue and 
improve alertness during the most critical stage of a long flight 
investigators said monday 
the federal aviation administration which cosponsored the 
study is reviewing the results officials said currently only 
military transport crews are allowed regular rest periods during 
flights some airlines in other countries also have adopted the 
practice investigators said 
the volunteer crews on northwest and united flights across the 
pacific were divided into a rest group and a nonrest group with 
two nasa investigators monitoring each crew on the flight deck 
the researchers found that given the opportunity to rest in 
their seats the pilots generally were able to fall asleep easily 
and sleep well the report said later these crew members 
demonstrated significantly higher levels of vigilance than their 
norest counterparts 
the report said the differences were especially dramatic near 
the end of the cruise phase of the flights just before the pilot 
starts the descent for landing 
pilots who took the preplanned rests on four successive flights 
also were less affected by having to make consecutive flights and 
flying at night the report said 
crew members who were allowed to rest each were given 40minute 
rest periods on a rotation basis so two pilots were always 
controlling the plane 
crew reaction was measured both by observations recorded in a 
log book by the nasa investigators and by portable monitoring 
equipment hooked to the pilots wrist 
previous research has shown that repeated time zone crossings 
often produce poor sleeping patterns particularly on eastbound 
flights when days are shortened 
nasa and faa studies also have found that pilots themselves 
often cannot accurately predict their own sleepiness 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

