a federal research group is calling for a more 
liberal policy on truck weights that it says could save 43 
billion a year in transport costs and cost railroads 750 million 
in lost revenue 
the national research council committee said all states should 
be given the option of exempting some trucks from a federal limit 
of 80000 pounds on the nations interstate highways it also 
recommended changes in the rules for bridge use that would allow 
heavier concrete mixers dump trucks and other trucks with shorter 
wheelbases 
the weight exemptions would be on the condition that they 
include fees to cover pavement and bridge wear said the committee 
which is made up of transportation experts from universities the 
industry and government the research council is linked to the 
national academy of sciences and the national academy of 
engineering 
the committee report recommends that heavy trucks still be 
restricted to designated routes comply with all other federal 
weight restrictions and comply with strict safety standards 
the exemptions would still be up to individual states but the 
report said it was not fair to prevent about half the states from 
allowing exemptions while the others who had exemptions before the 
current law can keep theirs 
if all states adopted the exemptions annual transportation 
savings for truckers could total 19 billion because of the use of 
more productive vehicles the report said 
