<TEXT>
the energy department said today it will cost 
about 6 billion in each of the next five years to store and clean 
up waste from nuclear weapons plants nearly 50 percent more than 
earlier was projected 
the agency blamed the higher cost estimates primarily on the 
discovery of additional wastes at doe sites and stricter government 
regulations that make the department and its contractors more 
susceptible to lawsuits 
it predicts that a doubling of cleanup staff may be necessary to 
meet the goals of does new fiveyear waste management plan through 
1996 
the revised fiveyear total through fiscal year 1995 will exceed 
286 billion compared with the 195 billion doe estimated six 
months ago according to a copy of the report summary made 
available monday by aides to rep norm dicks dwash 
such growth cannot now be managed responsibly and effectively 
given the inadequacy of the doe contractor industry and regulator 
infrastructure the report said 
preliminary estimates indicate that doe and its contractors 
must increase staff to at least two and onehalf times present 
levels it said 
a key member of congress said today he expected some increase in 
the cost estimates 
i always expect them to be higher but that is a mighty big 
difference between the estimate and the revised estimate said 
rep tom bevill dala chairman of the house appropriations 
energy and water subcommittee 
bevill said the new numbers will be closely scrutinized but he 
anticipates congress will support efforts to dispose of nuclear 
waste given the nations growing environmental concerns 
i think congress will be very supportive of anything dealing 
with the environment in this decade because our track record has 
not been so good in the past and people are now starting to realize 
it we are not getting very far very fast so far weve just 
talked about it he said 
dicks said the new figures demonstrate a need to finance 
research that will yield technology capable of disposing of the 
waste in a cheaper way 
the costs are going up we expected that said paul grimm 
assistant secretary for defense programs and director of the 
departments environmental safety and health coordination staff 
the more remediation we do the more we find that is going to 
have to be dealt with he said in confirming totals mentioned in 
the summary 
cost growth is to be expected as a normal consequence of this 
process however the cost estimates used in developing this 
fiscal year 199296 plan exceed what is considered a manageable 
growth rate the summary said 
these amounts challenge and almost certainly exceed the 
resources that can be brought to bear by doe its principal 
contractors the environmental restoration and waste management 
industries and state and federal regulators 
grimm said that in addition to new problems discovered at waste 
sites the increased costs are the result of stricter state and 
federal regulations governing waste disposal and cleanup 
perhaps the most significant and troubling factor in driving 
up cost estimates has been increased awareness of and exposure to 
civil and criminal liabilities for doe and contractor employees 
the report said 
grimm said some costs are expected to decline in the future as 
new technology uncovers cheaper ways to store and neutralize 
radioactive waste 
he said the new fiveyear plan through 1996 projects consecutive 
annual spending of 59 billion 64 billion 68 billion 63 
billion and 6 billion for a total of 314 billion 
the projections are consistent with earlier estimates that it 
would cost between 150 billion and 200 billion to clean up and 
store wastes at nuclear weapons plants nationwide over the next 30 
years grimm said 
the report stipulated that the estimates include unvalidated 
figures but it concluded that the costs have increased 
significantly since the last fiveyear plan was completed 
i dont think anyone was really caught by surprise said 
george behan dicks press secretary 
