thousands of east germans began taking refuge in western embassies 
in warsaw pact nations or fleeing across the hungarian border 
east germany eventually was forced to open its borders and its 
communist government fell 
albania a hardline stalinist state has been vigorously 
resisting the types of prodemocracy reforms that have been 
sweeping other eastern european countries 
however the communist leadership has signaled some willingness 
to increase foreign ties and grant citizens freedoms long denied 
under the rigid regime imposed by the late leader enver hoxha 
the albanian state news agency ata reported last month that 
under new travel regulations all albanians age 16 and over would 
be entitled to apply for a passport valid for five years 
ata had indicated the decree would take effect this month 
travel for albanias 3 million citizens has been difficult if 
not impossible for decades 
last month albania also pledged to adopt basic reforms and seek 
full membership in the conference on security and cooperation in 
europe albania is the only nation in europe that refused to sign 
the 1975 helsinki agreements on security and human rights 
other moderate reforms announced in recent weeks had included 
the abolition of the death penalty for those trying to flee the 
country and the acceptance of religion officially banned for 
decades 
albanian leaders had also announced they were seeking to mend 
relations with the superpowers 
