<TEXT>
two maleonly eating clubs at princeton 
university discriminate against women and must open their 
membership to females the state supreme court ruled today 
the high court ruled unanimously in an 11yearold sex 
discrimination case brought by sally frank a former princeton 
university student who is now a law professor at new york law 
school in new york city 
the court rejected the clubs argument that menonly clubs are 
permitted as long as they sever their relationship with the ivy 
league university 
im really thrilled ms frank said from washington dc 
im glad that the court decided to stop discrimination at 
princeton 
lawyers for the eating clubs could not be immediately reached 
for comment 
ms franks suit was against the ivy club and the tiger inn the 
only two among the universitys 13 private eating clubs that 
exclude women princeton began admitting women in 1969 
earlier this year the two clubs voted to admit women but two 
more rounds of voting must be conducted next year before women can 
join most juniors and seniors eat at the clubs housed near the 
princeton campus 
it is undisputed that the clubs had a general policy that 
excluded females from consideration as members the high court 
said it is also undisputed that the clubs applied this policy to 
frank when she tried to join the clubs 
in arguing the case before the supreme court attorneys for the 
two clubs had maintained that the clubs were private and not part 
of princeton university they said that gave the clubs the right to 
choose their membership 
but ms frank argued that the university has promoted the clubs 
in its publications and added that princeton has relied on them 
since more than 75 percent of the upperclassmen at the school eat 
at the clubs 
the supreme court ruling upheld a 1987 decision by the new 
jersey division on civil rights which ordered the clubs to begin 
admitting women that decision had been overturned by the appellate 
division of superior court which granted the clubs request for a 
new hearing because of prodecural errors 
but the supreme court said the clubs had already been afforded 
their administrative due process and it did not see any disputed 
facts 
frank had sued a third eating club but that club began admitting 
women in 1986 and settled with ms frank for 20000 the 
university was also named in the suit but also settled in 1986 
paying ms frank 27500 in legal fees and pledging to dissociate 
itself from sexually segregated clubs 
ms frank said she pursued the case because its outcome has 
implications beyond princeton 
for better or for worse people who graduate from princeton 
tend to take positions in leadership ms frank said if they 
learn while they are students at princeton that discrimination is 
acceptable then they are going to take that lesson with them i 
dont want them to learn that lesson 
