<TEXT>
the shootings reported in the albanian 
capital come at a time when that hardline communist nation has 
sought to implement cautious reforms and pledged to respect human 
rights 
reforms were initiated in may following a year of popular 
upheaval that ousted orthodox communist governments from most 
eastern european nations 
now scores of albanians apparently unimpressed with the scope 
of the reforms have fled to western embassies in the last few days 
in the largest known show of defiance against 45 years of stalinist 
rule the albanian government on tuesday acknowledged that rioting 
had broken out 
barely two weeks ago the albanian parliament a rubberstamp 
body for communist policy approved new travel regulations under 
which all citizens over 16 were gven the right to own a passport 
valid for five years 
such a concession would have been impossible under the late 
communist leader enver hoxha whose 40year rule ended with his 
death in 1985 
the tirana government firmly committed to marxismleninism as 
interpreted by soviet dictator josef stalin broke diplomatic ties 
with the soviet union and china after those countries moved away 
from what it considered orthodox communism 
britain and the united states severed ties with tirana after 
hoxhas communist party won elections in 1945 following a purge of 
anticommunists 
ramiz alia who took over after hoxhas death slowly began to 
open up the tiny balkan nation of 3 million establishing 
diplomatic ties with dozens of countries while ruling out renewed 
ties with the superpowers 
in may after the changes in the soviet bloc albanias 
communist leaders began announcing cautious political economic and 
