<DOCNO> AP900703-0095 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the nato alliance is no longer needed to keep 
the peace in europe and should be replaced by a security 
community of all european nations plus the united states the 
soviet union and canada a private group said tuesday 
the proposal by the british american security information 
council would do away with the 16nation north atlantic treaty 
organization and its cold war rival the warsaw pact which has 
been fractured by the democracy movements in eastern europe 
replacing these military blocs would be a paneuropean body 
based on the conference on security and cooperation in europe or 
csce an existing organization comprised of the two superpowers 
canada and all european nations except albania its main role now 
is to consider human rights and economic issues 
the report said the csce should be broadened and given an 
explicit link to the united nations france and some other european 
governments already have suggested this but the bush 
administration says csce should not be a replacement for nato 
questions about reshaping natos military and political roles 
are to be discussed at an alliance summit meeting thursday and 
friday in london the leaders are not expected to take any steps 
toward dissolving the alliance they are likely to say nato will 
change but will remain the central security body for europe 
at a meeting last month leaders of the sevennation warsaw pact 
agreed to keep that alliance intact at least until the conclusion 
this fall of a study on ways of transforming its role 
the proposal unveiled tuesday has been endorsed by numerous 
european and american politicians military experts and former 
government officials said david shorr associated director of the 
group that published the report 
paul warnke a former director of the us arms control and 
disarmament agency told a news conference the proposal was a 
sensible blueprint for the future 
warnke said he believed nato should be preserved only until a 
paneuropean replacement organization is in place he argued that 
the alliance will not be needed because the threat of a soviet 
attack on europe no longer exists 
among those endorsing the proposal according to shorr is 
pierre harmel the former belgian foreign minister who initiated a 
landmark nato study in 1967 that established the foundation for 
western relations with the soviet bloc through the 1980s 
the new report said a paneuropean security organization would 
have a permanent headquarters perhaps in berlin or prague 
czechoslovakia and an inner security council consisting of the 
united states the soviet union britain france and a reunified 
germany 
the organization would mediate disputes among european 
countries serve as a negotiating forum for european disarmament 
and verify and monitor agreed arms reductions members would sign a 
treaty disavowing any threat or use of force against each other 
</TEXT>
