<TEXT>
farmers spent an estimated 1241 billion on 
production expenses last year up 49 percent from 1184 billion 
in 1988 according to a preliminary report by the agriculture 
department released tuesday 
but that was still far below the record level of 1318 billion 
spent in 1981 just before a general financial crunch that stalled 
expansion in the nations agricultural sector 
in 1986 annual spending by farmers dropped to less than 106 
billion reflecting massive cutbacks in capital investments as land 
values plummeted and debts weighed heavily on so many 
the last report by the departments national agricultural 
statistics service showed 1989 expenditures rose for all major 
categories farm and land improvements which dropped 63 percent 
and fuel which declined slightly 
farm services which include rent comprised the largest 
expenditure by farmers at 267 billion up 07 percent from 1988 
these services accounted for 22 percent of overall production 
expenses 
feed expenses were estimated at 182 billion up 17 percent 
accounting for 15 percent of the total 1989 expenditures 
overall last years production expenditures averaged 57478 
per farm an increase of 2522 from 1988 
the analysis dealt only with production expenditures and did not 
include figures for net income or profits 
</TEXT>
