a wisconsin program that cuts welfare 
benefits of families whose children skip school suffers from 
serious administrative problems that unfairly penalize some 
recipients a state audit says 
the findings released monday drew strong responses from critics 
of the experimental learnfare program who contend gov tommy g 
thompson has touted it while hiding its problems 
by all accounts the learnfare program has been an 
administrative nightmare said state rep peter barca im very 
skeptical at this point 
learnfare authorized by the legislature in 1987 allows the 
state to cut a familys monthly aid to families with dependent 
children benefits if a school reports a student has been 
consistently absent without excuse 
the program applies to teenagers but thompson wants it 
expanded to include elementaryschool pupils the federal 
government has authorized the expansion but the legislature still 
must approve it 
barca said expansion is out of the question given the audit 
findings 
the audit said attendance measurement practices throughout the 
state are inconsistent and errors in paperwork by county social 
workers has resulted in some families being penalized without 
reason 
thompson had not seen the report and had no immediate comment 
his office said tuesday 
learnfare requires cooperation among the state department of 
health and social services the state department of public 
instruction county social service agencies and school districts 
which keep attendance records 
unfortunately cooperation among these agencies has fallen 
short of what is needed to ensure adequate program management 
the report said 
students ages 13 to 19 who dont attend classes regularly see 
their familys monthly benefits reduced by about 100 until schools 
report truancy has ended the states average monthly afdc payment 
is 517 
in general we found that significant weaknesses in 
administration of learnfare lead to some students being sanctioned 
who should not have been and other students who had too many 
unexcused absences not being sanctioned said state auditor dale 
cattanach 
in a review of 151 cases in milwaukee county in february 1990 
it said 13 cases were inappropriately sanctioned there were three 
instances in which students were truant without their families 
being penalized it said 
milwaukee school superintendent robert peterkin said monday his 
district the states largest will design a computerized reporting 
system to improve attendance monitoring 
thomas brophy director of milwaukee county social services 
said in a response letter than his agency will make every effort 
to correct this problem so that no one is sanctioned incorrectly 
brophy also said he doesnt believe significant improvements can 
be made unless his agency receives more money 
of the 30000 students subject to learnfare 48 percent live in 
milwaukee county where 75 percent the sanctions have been imposed 
the report said 
