secretary of defense dick cheney stands by his 
opposition to the purchase of v22 osprey tiltrotor aircraft for 
the marine corps despite a new study indicating it would be a good 
investment a spokesman said tuesday 
the secretary has concluded that the decision that he made 
last year remains valid spokesman pete williams told reporters 
that is that the v22 is an excellent aircraft but is simply 
too expensive to buy 
the institute for defense analysis a pentagonsponsored 
research group said in a report to congress on friday that the 
osprey could perform better on military missions and do so at less 
cost than helicopter alternatives favored by cheney 
williams said cheney disagrees with assumptions on which the 
report is based 
the osprey would be built jointly by boeing helicopters of 
philadelphia and bell helicoptertextron of fort worth texas 
it is designed to rise and hover like a helicopter and then fly 
like an airplane it would be used largely for militarytransport 
missions 
williams said cheney still believes the marine corps medium 
airlift requirement can be met by alternatives that cost less 
the institute said costs could be reduced by slowing the rate of 
production of the ospreys 
even at the reduced rate however williams said the ospreys 
would cost about 37 billion more during fiscal years 1991 
through 1997 than secretary of the navy h lawrence garrett iii 
recommended be spent on medium airlift 
the report also assumed that the marine corps could get by with 
fewer of the ospreys than originally proposed by flying more 
sorties at higher speeds 
williams said it was not known whether the aircraft could carry 
equipment slung under it at the proposed speed of 200 knots or 
whether the vehicles and other equipment would survive being 
carried at this speed 
williams also said the study appeared to overestimate the 
nearterm investment cost of helicopters 
the pentagon had once hoped to eventually buy about 650 ospreys 
members of congress from texas and pennsylvania with jobs at stake 
in their states have been among strong backers of the aircraft 
sen arlen specter rpa said on sunday once this report is 
in hand with these conclusions it is no longer possible for 
cheney to say credibly that the v22 is more expensive than 
alternatives 
