president bush said tuesday nato 
allies are expressing wide acceptance for his presummit 
proposals on nuclear strategy changes his plans include an 
alliance commitment not to use nuclear weapons except as a last 
resort other officials said 
bush leaves wednesday for the twoday nato summit beginning 
thursday in london and he has been telephoning leaders of the 
alliances other countries in advance of the meeting 
the president blending work with golf and other relaxation 
during a fiveday break at his oceanfront summer home planned to 
take in the local fireworks tuesday night from the deck of the us 
coast guard training barque eagle 
natos basic doctrine since 1967 has been that it would not rule 
out using nuclear weapons first if confronted with an invasion by 
superior conventional forces from the soviet union or its 
satellites 
however national security adviser brent scowcroft said tuesday 
the collapse of the sovietled warsaw pact justified changes in 
that flexible response policy 
scowcroft with bush in maine said the president had sent a 
letter to nato leaders trying to line up support for the changes 
he gave few specifics but administration officials aid 
privately that the bush plan would commit the 16nation alliance to 
ease their nuclearweapons stance at least to the extent of calling 
for use only as a last resort 
bush also steered clear of details as he met with reporters 
outside his vacation home but he said the general approach that 
were proposing seems to be getting wide acceptance 
scowcroft at a later news briefing said the summit takes place 
at a moment of significant historic transition in europe 
the overriding issue is how to adapt the western alliance to 
the changing security environment in europe including the 
collapse of the warsaw pact the changes in eastern europe 
and the turmoil thats going on in the soviet union scowcroft 
said 
he said natos strategy must recognize that shortly there 
will no longer be armies facing each other directly across a 
boundary 
instead he said the united states is looking for the soviets 
to withdraw their troops from eastern europe he added its a 
very different matter to attack a few hundred yards across a border 
than it is to move forces up several hundred miles into eastern 
europe to be prepared for an attack 
one has to look at the issues of forward defense flexible 
response all the kinds of strategies that nato pursues now to see 
how they might be modified to fit those new circumstances said 
the national security adviser 
he said bushs proposals are not bombshells but they are 
significant because this is a significant time scowcroft said 
the united states already has gotten favorable reactions from 
five or six nato allies 
bush conferred at his oceanfront home tuesday with vice 
president dan quayle treasury secretary nicholas brady trade 
representative carla hills and other senior officials to prepare 
for next mondays economic summit in houston bush will fly to 
texas from europe late friday 
bush said he hoped the economic summit bringing together the 
leaders of the worlds seven largest industrialized nations would 
bring progress on trade 
before that the nato allies are holding their third summit in 
the past year as the alliance prepares to welcome a new united 
germany into its ranks a move that soviet president mikhail s 
gorbachev staunchly opposes 
bush said he hopes the nato summit will help persuade the 
soviets that a unified germany in nato is no threat to the soviet 
union he said if there are certain things we can do to expand 
natos role that drive that point home so much the better 
while sympathetic to gorbachevs problems at home bush 
reiterated tuesday that he remains opposed to western economic aid 
for the soviet union a subject sure to come up at one or both of 
the summits 
scowcroft said i think the soviets will be looking at this 
summit very carefully 
its a difficult issue for the soviet union not only is their 
alliance collapsing and the kind of defense barrier to their west 
that they count on for 40 years but the sort of crown jewel of 
that defensive barrier is now being proposed to join the core of an 
alliance that im sure they tell their little children is evil 
incarnate scowcroft said 
in addition to agreeing to use nuclear weapons only as a last 
resort administration officials say bush has suggested other moves 
to overcome soviet anxieties including eventually scrapping the 
1470 us nucleartipped artillery shells now based mostly in west 
germany reducing or eliminating an arsenal of 1560 us nuclear 
bombs deployed in seven nato countries and pulling back troops from 
forward deployment 
