<TEXT>
the judge in mayor marion barrys drug case 
argued tuesday that he is entitled to bar nation of islam leader 
louis farrakhan and a dissident roman catholic priest from the 
trial because their presence probably would intimidate witnesses 
and jurors 
the justice department in a separate filing supported judge 
thomas penfield jacksons contention that neither barry farrakhan 
nor george augustus stallings is legally entitled to ask for relief 
from the us circuit court of appeals for the district of columbia 
the american civil liberties union which brought the suit on 
behalf of barry farrakhan and stallings will respond wednesday to 
the justice and jackson filings said local aclu legal director 
arthur spitzer 
when he barred farrakhan from the courtroom last wednesday 
jackson said that the muslim leaders presence would be 
potentially disruptive and very likely intimidating he cited the 
same reasoning in denying stallings entry to the proceedings 
in his submission to the appeals court the judge wrote 
farrakhan and stallings by reason of their extraordinary 
publicity and their widely known and highly controversial views on 
matters directly pertainting to the ongoing trial would be likely 
to send an impermissible message to and to distract disrupt and 
intimidate both jurors and witnesses 
barry can take up the matter with the appeals court if appeals a 
conviction in his drug possession and perjury case the judge wrote 
revs farrakhan and stallings are not parties to any case or 
proceeding in the district court jackson wrote it follows 
that because there is no proper jurisdiction in this court for 
them there is no valid basis for any requested relief 
district courts posess considerable discretion to exclude 
specific spectators in order to ensure that jurors and witnesses 
are free of distraction disruption and intimidation the judge 
added 
jackson concluded that his actions were well within my 
discretion under the unique circumstances that barrys trial has 
produced 
the judge announced his decision to exclude farrakhan and 
stallings while the jury in barrys case was outside the courtroom 
in both instances barry had sought to give one of his special 
guest passes to the men 
in his initial filing spitzer argued that jackson must present 
proof that farrakhan and stallings would disrupt the trial he also 
claimed that jacksons order violated the mayors constitutional 
right to a public trial 
but the justice department wrote that since the press and 
members of the public are allowed to attend all proceedings 
defendant barrys right to a public trial is preserved 
about a dozen of farrakhans followers have protested jacksons 
actions outside the courthouse this week while stallings has 
decried jacksons decision as well 
the story has become a sidelight in barrys case both farrakhan 
and stallings who are black claim that they have been excluded 
from the proceedings because of their race barry and his backers 
have been suggesting for months that the case against the mayor was 
racially motivated 
thirteen of the 18 jurors are black 
jackson who is white has refused to comment on the matter 
outside his legal filings 
