<DOCNO> AP900703-0134 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
engineers on both coasts will begin tests 
after the fourth of july to find the mysterious fuel leaks that 
have grounded americas space shuttle fleet for an indefinite time 
we dont expect the standdown to be extensive nasas space 
flight chief william lenoir said tuesday but he conceded that 
we dont know exactly how long its going to be 
a 17inch fuel line removed from the shuttle columbia was 
brought to shuttle builder rockwell international in california for 
the tests along with the complicated hardware that connects the 
line to the orbiter and its huge tank 
the shuttle atlantis still is on the launch pad at the kennedy 
space center in florida awaiting a sequence of tests being worked 
out this week both shuttles leaked supercold liquid hydrogen as 
their tanks were being filled recently causing their launches to 
be postponed 
the fuel transfer system also includes a fourinch pipe used to 
pressurize the tank and a twoinch line that pumps helium early in 
the fueling process 
the pipes are in two parts one half attached to the orbiter 
the other to the fuel tank they are connected until eight minutes 
into a flight when the tank is empty and jettisoned the half on 
the orbiter is reused the other half is destroyed with the tank 
engineers have detected leaks in both the 17inch and 4inch 
lines but dont know exactly where lenoir said the leaks show 
only when the liquid hydrogen is flowing through the pipes at 
minus 431 degrees fahrenheit 
on the 4inch side there is a leak but it may be within 
specifications which means we dont have a concern with it 
lenoir said it would appear there is a more significant problem 
with the 17inch and thats where we ought to focus our attention 
the tests in downey will be conducted first with gaseous helium 
then gaseous nitrogen then gaseous hydrogen lenoir said if that 
doesnt reveal the leak engineers will use liquid nitrogen and 
finally liquid hydrogen 
the fuel lines and fittings from the tanks on columbia and 
atlantis are numbers three and four in a batch of eight that failed 
acceptance tests in 1983 then were passed in a subsequent 
procedure the first two were used in march and november last year 
to get discovery into orbit 
lenoir said however that about 20 such units had failed when 
they were first tested only to pass on a retest and we didnt 
change procedures in order to pass these 
on nasas other big problem the outoffocus 15 billion 
hubble space telescope the space agency said that some fuzzy 
images may be improved through the same computer process that 
cleaned up photos taken by the voyager spacecraft 
but said ed weiler a hubble project scientist the pictures 
will still be less clear than scientists originally expected 
weiler said a team of experts was being selected to determine 
how much of the fuzz ball now being seen by the space telescope 
can be turned into crisp pictures through computer techniques 
he called the improvement of pictures through computers 
something of a black art but he said other experts in the 
field are certain they can improve some of hubbles views 
ill believe it when i see it weiler told reporters 
well let the experts play with the images people in the field 
say there is a lot of hope there 
weiler emphasized however that the computerenhancing 
technique is only an effort to salvage some good from a 
fundamentally flawed telescope 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

