a soviet helicopter pilot hailed as a hero for 
trying to douse the 1986 fire at the chernobyl nuclear plant 
despite intense radiation died at age 53 after developing 
radiationrelated leukemia 
anatoly grishchenko died late monday at the fred hutchinson 
cancer research center the final cause of death was listed as 
heart failure brought on by a lung infection 
doctors said tuesday that grishchenko may have been doomed by 
delays in getting him treatment still grishchenkos soviet 
physician said the treatment he received at the center was the best 
anywhere and said she could not fault it 
ill try to tell my chief and all the soviet people and all 
the soviet physicians that patient grishchenko had the best 
treatment he could have here at this center dr eugenia margulis 
told a news conference tuesday 
everybody was taking care of him not only the physicians and 
the nurses and the staff but all the people from seattle 
she said grishchenko the only chernobyl victim to be treated in 
the united states received more than 100 cards and letters daily 
from around the country 
seattle mayor norm rice ordered flags on city buildings to fly 
at halfstaff tuesday in grishchenkos honor 
in april 1986 grishchenko repeatedly flew his helicopter 
through the intensely radioactive gases above the smoldering 
chernobyl plant dumping sand and cement to entomb the crippled 
reactor after it exploded 
he was among a handful of participants designated heroes of the 
soviet union that countrys highest honor when soviet leader 
mikhail gorbachev visited america in june for summit talks with 
president bush he sent a top aide to give grishchenko a 
handwritten note praising his bravery 
after the disaster grishchenko suffered acute radiation 
sickness he was found to have leukemia last year he was flown to 
seattle april 11 and a bone marrow transplant was performed later 
that month 
doctors thought his chances of recovery good and hutchinson 
associate director john hansen said he was out of bed doing 
exercises after the transplant 
but a lung infection flared up and grishchenko underwent 
surgery june 12 his condition worsened and on june 15 he was 
placed on a respirator 
hutchinson dr finn petersen who assisted in the transplant 
said a combination of soviet red tape and difficulty finding a 
marrow donor contributed to the infection which he said developed 
when grishchenko got pneumonia in january and persisted until it 
cut off oxygen to his bloodstream 
he probably would not have developed this infection if we 
didnt have the wait petersen said 
we should have done the transplant last fall hansen added 
grishchenkos initial response to treatment showed promise for 
others said dr patrick beatty director of the centers unrelated 
transplant program 
despite his heavy radiation exposure in the past he 
actually did extremely well in the transplant beatty said 
