british prime minister margaret thatcher have urged the anc to 
give up violence the ancs armed campaign has been largely dormant 
in the past year but anc leaders said they could not end it until 
police and troops quit firing on unarmed black protesters 
mandela and other black leaders plan to meet with south african 
officials on his return from a 14nation world tour 
earlier tuesday mandela struggled to untangle himself from the 
northern ireland conflict and focus attention on britains 
opposition to sanctions against south africa 
he denied having called on britain to negotiate with the irish 
republican army insisting he was just expressing his belief that 
all conflicts should be settled peacefully british officials have 
refused to hold talks with the ira saying it is a terrorist group 
mandelas replies to questions on the ira at a dublin news 
conference on monday made frontpage headlines and continued to dog 
him at meetings tuesday with members of parliament and foreign 
secretary douglas hurd 
hurd said mandela the deputy president of the anc cleared up 
the position as far as he was concerned 
i expressed the strong feelings of everyone here that the ira 
are rejects of the political system he said having failed to 
persuade people in free elections they turn to murder and 
destruction 
britain is promoting negotiations between the main protestant 
and catholic parties of northern ireland and has suggested the ira 
can be drawn in if it disavows violence 
the ira has waged a campaign of bombings and shootings in an 
effort to force british troops out of northern ireland the ira 
wants to unite northern ireland with the irish republic and set up 
a socialist state 
mrs thatcher who narrowly escaped an ira bomb in 1984 was 
expected to reiterate britains position when she meets mandela on 
wednesday 
even before the ira issue arose britain was already expected to 
be the most difficult stop on mandelas world tour 
mrs thatcher openly opposes sanctions against south africa and 
wants those imposed by the european community relaxed as a reward 
for president fw de klerks reform program mandela insists the 
anc alone should decide when sanctions can be lifted 
but their talks signify the aboutface in british policy since 
1987 when mrs thatcher branded the anc a typical terrorist 
organization and said she wouldnt talk to it 
mandela said the possibility is always there that his talks 
with mrs thatcher might narrow their differences 
mandela 71 arrived from dublin the irish capital nursing a 
severe cold and canceled some of the engagements on his twoday 
london schedule 
meeting 200 members of parliament assembled by the allparty 
southern africa committee mandela insisted he was not trying to 
interfere in the northern ireland conflict 
i expressed no opinion whatsoever on the actual conflict 
between the ira and the british government mandela insisted 
what i said was to point out that our approach as the anc is 
that all conflicts wherever in the world they are from should be 
settled peacefully he said 
in dublin when asked about the ira mandela replied what we 
would like to see is that the british government and the ira should 
adopt precisely the line that we have taken in regard to our own 
internal situation 
there is nothing better than opponents sitting down to resolve 
their problems in a peaceful manner 
the controversy was one of the few jarring notes on mandelas 
otherwise triumphant trip to urge continued international pressure 
to end apartheid in south africa 
mandela was freed from prison in february he had been jailed 
since 1962 and was serving a life term for sabotage and plotting to 
overthrow the government 
