wrights lawsuit centered on two chemicals in loxene a 
pesticide known as trichlorocarbonilide or tcc and 
pentachlorophenol a substance known as penta that is more widely 
used as a pesticide and wood preservative 
despite being warned as early as 1955 that penta was unsafe 
because it caused skin irritations basf wyandotte then wyandotte 
chemical corp instructed booth hospital how to use loxene in 
final laundry rinses to kill mildew the lawsuit contended 
the salvation army which operated the nowdefunct booth 
hospital for unwed mothers previously agreed to pay wright 5000 
and dow chemical co settled for 60000 bogard said dow and 
monsanto co were accused because they manufactured penta and tcc 
monsanto was dropped as a defendant 
