<TEXT>
the federal election commission wants to know 
whether us subsidiaries of foreign companies should be able to 
run political action committees in this country 
the commission voted 41 last thursday to instruct its general 
counsel to draft a list of questions on which public comment should 
be sought 
political action committees or pacs are organized by 
companies unions trade associations and interest groups of all 
kinds to solicit money from their members and give it to candidates 
contributions from such pacs long have been controversial 
federal election law bars citizens of foreign countries from making 
donations to congressional and presidential elections but foreign 
corporations with wholly owned american subsidiaries are allowed to 
have their subsidiaries establish pacs just like any other company 
soliciting from their employees who are american citizens 
critics contend that allows foreign interests to influence 
elections 
the proposal to seek public comment was offered by commissioner 
john mcgarry one of three democrat appointees to the panel the 
two other democrats and republican thomas josefiak voted to open 
the issue to comment but josefiak said his vote should not be 
taken as an indication he favored a ban on such pacs or any changes 
to existing laws just that he wanted to see what comments would 
come in 
observers of the fec believe the panel would split 33 if a 
commissioner sought an outright ban on such pacs but the 
commission believes it does not have that power and over the years 
has asked congress to deal with the issue 
sen lloyd bentsen dtexas the democratic nominee for vice 
president in the 1988 election recently wrote a dear colleague 
letter suggesting it was time for congress to determine whether 
pacs of foreignowned us companies should be restricted or banned 
</TEXT>
