<TEXT>
an oil pipeline company tuesday proposed 
construction of a 500 million terminal and pipeline system to take 
oil through puget sound without tankers 
the proposal which revived a decadeold idea immediately met 
opposition from some environmentalists who fear moving oil through 
the sound by pipeline or tanker risks spills 
trans mountain pipe line co ltd of vancouver british 
columbia said it wants to build a terminal at low point on the 
strait of juan de fuca which runs between the united states and 
canada 
the company would lay two partly submerged parallel pipelines 
that would carry millions of barrels of crude oil about 80 miles to 
upper puget sound 
one of the proposed pipelines would carry oil coming in from 
alaska and asia for processing the other would meet an existing 
pipeline from the canadian province of alberta that carries crude 
oil bound for export 
trans mountains first hurdle will be convincing puget sound 
refiners british petroleum atlantic richfield texaco and shell 
oil to use the pipeline at a cost trans mountain estimates at 
about 40 cents a barrel more than the average cost of transporting 
the oil by tanker 
trans mountain president richard stokes said initial discussions 
have been encouraging arco and british petroleum spokesmen said 
they were willing to consider the proposal stokes said agreement 
would be needed in order to secure the 500 million needed for the 
project 
trans mountain also would need approval from the state energy 
facilities site evaluation council after a long public review 
process stokes said 
the announcement came several hours after the release of a 
report by a regional oilspill task force that recommends serious 
consideration of an offshore terminal and pipeline system to reduce 
the risk of oil spills in puget sound 
the statesbritish columbia task force said the risk of oil 
spills under current circumstances can only increase with expected 
rises in tanker traffic in the region 
crude oil shipments into puget sound which total about 161 
million barrels annually are expected to increase by 5 percent a 
year this decade the report said with accompanying increases in 
the traffic of refined oil 
shipments from canada to asian markets also are on the rise the 
task force said and can be expected to increase more than fivefold 
this decade 
gov booth gardner who would have the power to veto the 
pipeline project considers the proposal worthy of study said 
gubernatorial spokesman dick milne 
environmentalists dismissed it 
here we go again said jeff parsons a spokesman for the 
washington audubon society recalling the bitter fight a decide ago 
over a similar proposal that plan was ultimately junked by 
thengov john spellman in 1982 
parsons said neither pipelines nor tankers are good options for 
hauling oil in the sound 
the best option is to establish a national energy policy that 
severely reduces our reliance on oil he said the only way to 
really prevent spills is to leave oil in the ground 
the task force said a terminal and pipeline system combined 
with other spill preventative steps would reduce the threat of a 
large sound spill by 66 percent 
the proposed pipelines would run by land from the terminal about 
12 miles west of port angeles on the olympic peninsula to admiralty 
inlet 
from there the lines would run underwater to whidbey island in 
the sound cross the island then go underwater again until 
reaching the mainland near stanwood on the eastern side of the 
puget sound the lines then would run north to connect with an 
existing pipeline system at burlington 
</TEXT>
