<TEXT>
two maleonly eating clubs at princeton 
university must end a centuryold tradition of excluding women and 
open their doors to the opposite sex the states highest court 
ruled tuesday 
the state supreme court rejected arguments by the ivy club and 
the tiger inn that they were private entities separate from the ivy 
league university and not subject to the states 
antidiscrimination laws 
it would be disingenuous for the clubs to assert that they 
could ever exist apart from princeton university the 
sevenmember court said in a unanimous opinion the clubs gather 
their membership from princeton and in turn provide the service 
of feeding princeton students 
because of this the clubs lack the distinctly private nature 
that would exempt them from discrimination laws the court said 
the ruling stems from an 11yearold sex discrimination case 
brought by sally frank a former princeton student who is now a 
professor at new york law school in new york city 
im really thrilled ms frank said from washington dc 
im glad that the court decided to stop discrimination at 
princeton 
stockton williams 22 undergraduate president of tiger inn 
said the ruling would be appealed to the us supreme court 
we feel that all of the affairs of the club should be decided 
by the members including who we allow in williams said 
barbara strapp nelson a lawyer for the ivy club said the club 
strongly disagreed with the courts ruling which she said 
overlooked the constitutionally protected right of freedom of 
association 
i think this case has often been viewed as an emotional 
womens rights type of case whereas its really a case involving 
whether the government should be intervening in decisions made 
by individuals as to who they socialize with ms nelson said 
she said the ivy clubs governing board would examine its 
choices before deciding whether to appeal 
in 1979 ms frank sued the ivy club and the tiger inn the only 
two among the universitys 13 private eating clubs that exclude 
women princeton began admitting women in 1969 
most juniors and seniors pay membership fees to eat at the 
clubs housed near the princeton campus 
both clubs voted earlier this year to admit women but two more 
rounds of voting must be conducted next year before any can join 
it is undisputed that the clubs had a general policy that 
excluded females from consideration as members the court said 
it is also undisputed that the clubs applied this policy to 
frank when she tried to join 
attorneys for the two clubs maintained that as private entities 
they had the right to choose their membership 
but ms frank argued that the university has promoted the clubs 
in its publications and that princeton has relied on the clubs 
since they feed more than 75 percent of upperclass students 
tuesdays ruling upheld a 1987 decision by the new jersey 
division on civil rights which ordered the clubs to begin 
admitting women that decision was overturned by the appellate 
division of superior court which granted the clubs request for a 
new hearing because of procedural errors 
but the supreme court said the clubs already had been afforded 
their administrative due process and said it did not see any 
disputed facts 
ms frank had sued a third eating club but that club began 
admitting women in 1986 and settled with ms frank for 20000 
the university also was named in the lawsuit but settled in 
1986 paying ms frank 27500 in legal fees and pledging to 
dissociate itself from sexually segregated clubs 
under tuesdays ruling the two clubs must pay ms frank a total 
of 5000 plus legal fees to be determined by the court 
</TEXT>
