leaders of the prosandinista national workers front called the 
strike on monday to protest firings and demand a say in national 
economic policy a role the union contends it is guaranteed by the 
constitution 
government officials said that as of tuesday only about 800 
employees in three ministries were on strike at the managua 
mayors office 1200 workers who had joined the walkout on monday 
reached an agreement with the mayor and returned to work tuesday 
union officials however gave vastly different figures 
lucio jimenez leader of the sandinista workers center another 
union federation called the strike a full success and said a 
total of 42000 employees had stayed away from their jobs in 
government ministries the customs service at managuas 
international airport and various stateowned industries 
including construction textile metalworking and beer plants 
an airport customs employee and workers at some of the 
stateowned companies including the milca bottling plant 
contradicted jimenez and said they were working normally 
telecommunications and postal workers stopped service including 
international telephone service for one hour tuesday in support of 
the strike service then returned to normal bus transportation 
electricity banking water or other services continued 
uninterrupted 
riot police and patrol cars cordoned off president violeta 
barrios de chamorros offices keeping away vehicles and 
pedestrians and police were on duty outside state offices to 
guarantee entry for the public and employees who wanted to work 
labor minister francisco rosales declared the strike illegal 
late monday saying it was strictly political and aimed at 
sabotaging the recovery program 
the national workers front has sought an injunction from the 
appeals court against the decree and protested the banning of 
pickets by the interior ministry 
if the court agrees that the strike is illegal the government 
can fire strikers outright something it would like to do to trim 
the bureaucracy 
the governments economic plans include returning most 
stateowned companies to the private sector and reorganizing the 
government both moves expected to involve job cutbacks 
the strike differs sharply from a walkout by 65000 government 
employees in may that paralyzed activity across the country 
including international flights and telephone service 
in may the demands focused on salary increases and a sandinista 
law protecting government workers jobs and benefits that strike 
ended after the unions won 100 percent pay hikes and a promise that 
the government would not retaliate a provision union leaders say 
has been violated 
the chamorro government they say has fired more than 800 
employees most of them sandinistas since it took office april 25 
two months after winning general elections 
the new government views the current walkout as a move by the 
sandinistas to assert themselves as an opposition power 
while most government employees are holdovers from the previous 
government many would rather try to hold onto their jobs than give 
open support to the sandinistas 
very few are going to support the strike because no one wants 
to risk being fired said a telephone operator at the 
construction and transportation ministry who asked not to be 
identified 
unemployment is officially estimated at 34 percent of the work 
force of 12 million with the end of the nineyear war by 
usbacked contra rebels against the sandinistas the number of 
jobless is growing 
</TEXT>
