<TEXT>
many women over 50 years old dont get mammograms 
because they mistakenly think they dont need them according to an 
american medical association study released tuesday 
the study found that while more than 90 percent of the women 
polled in various surveys visited a doctor regularly just 25 
percent to 41 percent received xray breast examinations during the 
previous year 
most of the women who didnt receive a mammography said they 
skipped the breast cancer screening procedure because they didnt 
think it was necessary or because they didnt have any breast 
problems the study found the nextlargest group said their 
doctors never recommended the examination 
this relatively low utilization of breast cancer screening may 
help to explain why breast cancer mortality rates have not declined 
over the past three decades the report says 
the american cancer society recommends women have one mammogram 
between the ages of 35 and 39 one every to two years between 40 
and 49 and one annually after that 
the national cancer institute and the national health interview 
survey interviewed 7011 women from 50 to 74 years old across the 
country in different studies between 1987 and 1989 the combined 
results were reported in this weeks edition of the journal of the 
american medical association 
lesseducated and poorer women were even less likely to receive 
breast cancer screenings the survey found 
doctors are hesitant to recommend the procedure because they 
feel patients are reluctant to get mammograms or will object to the 
costs the study indicated but few women surveyed said they failed 
to get one because of the cost or because of radiation fears 
</TEXT>
