lauded the economic stabilization accomplished by postcommunist 
polands shock reform plan but urged even more rapid steps 
toward creating a market economy 
the world bank has loaned poland 781 million for five projects 
since lending to the country resumed in january officials say 
about 2 billion more in loans are envisioned during the next two 
fiscal years 
the new loan is to help wean poland from its dependence on 
inefficient and environmentally damaging coal 
the world bank mission in warsaw will provide advice technical 
assistance and financial services for polands economic overhaul 
proposed terms for a 300 million structural adjustment 
loan representing world bank endorsement of polands plan for 
shifting from centrallyplanned socialism to marketdriven 
capitalism are being reviewed by the government 
the loan is to be used to assist poland in reorganizing its debt 
to the west now estimated at 422 billion approval by the world 
bank directors is expected by fall officials say 
whether we will be able to continue this level of lending 
operations is dependent on poland being able to support and 
implement a debt management strategy that will return it to a 
reasonable level of creditworthiness wapenhans said 
the accomplishments of the first phase of the economic reform 
including the curbing of runaway inflation are impressive 
wapenhans said 
but he said the accompanying very severe contraction of the 
economy including a 40 percent drop in real incomes and declining 
industrial output leads the world bank to hope for even more 
rapid implementation of parts of the plan 
in the second phase of reforms a key step is continuing to 
strip away artificial pricing structures that were a hallmark of 
the highly subsidized socialist economy 
the energy development loan calls for increasing domestic 
natural gas supplies by about 20 percent said mieczyslaw 
kaczmarczyk director of the energy enterprise being supported by 
the loan 
he said longterm negligence had retarded development of gas 
and other clean energy resources noting that poland produced more 
natural gas in the 1970s than it does now 
coal has traditionally been a key source of foreign export 
income for poland which has sent most of its lowsulfur coal 
abroad and used the remainder at home resulting in a dramatic air 
pollution problem 
the washingtonbased world bank is supported by more than 150 
countries poland rejoined in june 1986 
