<TEXT>
for three months imelda marcos suffered through 
daily ridicule bouts of illness and endless hours of courtroom 
testimony about her profligate spending 
after a federal court jury declared on monday that she was 
innocent of racketeering obstructing justice and mail fraud mrs 
marcos on her 61st birthday got down and walked the length of st 
patricks cathedral on her knees 
it was the sort of center stage drama mrs marcos relished 
during her years as the first lady of the philippines a woman who 
rose from obscure beginnings to call herself the mother of the 
nation and traveled among her people like a queen 
imelda remedios visitacion romualdez was born july 2 1929 to 
vicente romualdez a lawyer sometimes portrayed as from the poorer 
branch of one of the philippines most prominent families 
a beauty contest winner she became the wife of ferdinand 
marcos a brilliant lawyer and selfproclaimed world war ii hero 
when marcos was elected president in 1965 the couple were compared 
by an adoring world press to us president john f kennedy and his 
first lady jacqueline 
they had three children daughter imee now living in exile in 
morocco daughter irene and son ferdinand jr known as bong bong 
meanwhile benigno aquino jr who had been one of imeldas 
suitors married corazon cojuangco he was driven into exile in the 
united states by marcos and was murdered on his return in 1983 
although they emphatically denied it marcos and his wife were 
widely accused by filipino critics of ordering aquinos 
assassination and his death put in motion the events that drove 
marcos from power three years later 
in the 20 years that marcos served as president meldy was 
always at his side an inseparable part of the power structure that 
doled out favors and collected tribute 
marcos made her his envoy to the united nations and designated 
her presidential envoy plenipotentiary dispatching her on good 
will missions to the soviet union china and other countries 
she was credited by the promarcos media with negotiating oil 
deals and diplomatic settlements later as the appointed governor 
of metro manila she built hotels schools hospitals and a 
cultural center as minister of human settlements she tried to 
improve housing and services for the impoverished 
in an overwhelmingly roman catholic country of 62 million she 
practiced her religion publicly and for political effect 
she brought celebrities such as actor george hamilton into her 
inner circle traveled with a coterie of loyalists known as the 
blue ladies for their dress and threw frequent parties at 
which she invariably sang to her guests sometimes rendering songs 
that she wrote herself 
she became famous for spending sprees at boutiques department 
stores and jewelers during frequent trips to new york and travels 
elsewhere 
critics assailed her jetset life style while much of her 
country struggled in poverty she responded by insisting that the 
people admired her and drew hope from her example of a better 
life 
it all ended in ignominy in 1986 when after calling a spot 
election to cement his control and apparently losing to mrs aquino 
in balloting riddled by official fraud marcos was driven from 
power by a peoples revolution and fled to exile in hawaii 
left behind along with thousands of documents that would later 
be used to incriminate the marcoses in a vast web of corruption 
were imeldas shoes more than 1000 pairs closer to 3000 by 
some estimates 
the government accused her of helping to steal 222 million from 
her nations treasury and using the money to invest secretly in new 
york real estate and other items most of the prospective jurors 
interviewed for the trial said they knew little about her except 
that she had a lot of shoes 
in court she wore black mourning clothes for her husband who 
died last september one new york newspaper newsday printed a 
photo of her shoes every day of the trial 
twice she suffered attacks of high blood pressure interrupting 
the trial and prompting doctors to fit her with a special monitor 
another time she was hospitalized for four days after collapsing at 
the defense table vomiting blood from what was diagnosed as a 
stomach ailment 
on monday after three months enough testimony to fill nearly 
6000 pages of transcript and five days of deliberation the jury 
acquitted mrs marcos on all charges 
imelda marcos pronounced herself vindicated and went to 
church to pray but in victory she was denied the thing that she 
has professed to want most the right to go home and take her 
husbands body with her for burial 
a spokeswoman for the aquino government said it still considered 
imelda marcos a security threat and the official policy 
barring her return had not changed 
</TEXT>
