<TEXT>
the day a stranger forced his way into 
nancy ziegenmeyers car cursing her for being white and savagely 
assaulting her was just the first of two events that changed her 
life 
the second came eight months later on july 11 1989 when she 
decided to tell the story of her rape to the des moines register 
one of the nations largest newspapers and to do it without the 
cloak of anonymity 
few women have opened the doors to their private hell in such a 
public way and the response invitations to speak requests for 
interviews from journalists the world over has been 
overwhelmingly positive 
the response tells me society is ready to deal with this 
crime she said i think society is saying yes were ready 
to learn teach us 
mrs ziegenmeyer came forward because of a column written by 
register editor geneva overholser exploring the refusal of her 
newspaper and others to identify rape victims the purpose she 
wrote was to protect victims from new pain but it instead 
unwittingly reenforces the canard that somehow the victim is at 
fault 
a troubling consequence of our reluctance to talk about rape 
is that we rarely confront it directly she wrote we shy away 
from thinking about rape we shy away from its victims 
as long as rape is deemed unspeakable and is therefore not 
fully honest and honestly spoken of the public outrage will be 
muted as well 
mrs ziegenmeyer called the paper and agreed to be interviewed 
at length for stories on the condition they not appear before the 
man accused in the crime bobby lee smith came to trial smith was 
convicted of firstdegree kidnapping and sentenced to life in 
prison with no chance for parole 
the series by reporter jane schorer ran this year from late 
february through early march it started with the rape including 
spare but graphic details of what happened that early saturday 
morning in november 1988 and continued with mrs ziegenmeyers 
frustrating attempts to deal with her family the trial and 
everyday life 
i think it was the dreary dailyness of her story that made it 
so powerful ms overholser said 
we knew it would be a powerful story in iowa but we had no 
idea it would be in such demand nationwide the editor said 
media people indulged in a feeding frenzy to share the story 
and get reaction she said 
mrs ziegenmeyer wasnt the first smalltown woman who was raped 
when she visited the city and she wasnt the first to tell her 
story by name 
ive decided that timing is everything the editor said 
this seems to be the season for the issue in new york for 
example there was some disagreement over whether to report the 
name of a woman who was raped by a gang of youths while jogging in 
central park 
mrs ziegenmeyer feels her story touched so many because it is 
not hers alone its the story of thousands of other women 
across the country 
my single intent when i worked with geneva and jane was to 
help other victims and help society understand that this is a crime 
of violence just short of murder said mrs ziegenmeyer in a 
telephone interview from her home in grinnell about 40 miles east 
of des moines 
the only difference is that the rapist leaves the victims 
alive 
the interviews were cathartic she said but not essential for 
her recovery 
a great amount of healing had already taken place before the 
story was published she said i remember the first time i 
laughed one of those laughs were you laugh until you cry it felt 
like a ton of bricks were lifted off my shoulder i thought my 
god im human i can do something other than cry 
after that i began to heal she said 
she and ms overholser emphasized that her decision to come 
forward was not a recommendation for other victims the editor said 
the paper would continue its policy of omitting names of victims 
unless they preferred otherwise 
the good of this story is the realization that this can happen 
to anyone said karen muelhaupt a rape counselor for polk county 
most women already know the men who rape them ms muelhaupt 
said the man who jumps out of the bushes is a relatively rare 
occurrence she said 
at least 80 percent of victims are assaulted by acquaintances 
she said and almost all are raped by someone of the same race 
mrs ziegenmeyer white was assaulted by a black stranger 
the only negative letters ive gotten are a few who approach 
the racial aspect of the story said mrs ziegenmeyer i 
certainly think there was a racist in my car that morning but it 
wasnt me 
another strangerrape victim mary williams of des moines said 
mrs ziegenmeyers story did a lot to take away the myth that 
weve all heard that somehow the rape victim brought this on 
but she said the story left the impression that as soon as 
rapists are caught they are out of their victims lives forever 
mrs williams said the man who assaulted her was sentenced to up to 
25 years and could be released at any time she is certain he will 
try to attack again 
in an introduction to the story ms overholser wrote that mrs 
ziegenmeyers story was simply that one womans story 
we never say the story is representative the editor said 
all we were doing was telling a hell of a story that nancy let us 
tell with her name on it 
