the cuba of jorge mas canosas dreams is an 
economic dynamo engorged by us investment it is a veritable 
suburb of florida it is free 
and who would be president of this postcastro cuba some 
observers say mas already is campaigning for the job but the 
50yearold businessman arguably the most powerful cuban exile in 
this country denies it 
what im doing is very american dreaming with a model of a 
republic for some its a utopia for me its a reachable 
dream he said 
for 30 years since he left cuba as a student in 1960 mas has 
been enmeshed in the anticastro movement his vehicle has been the 
cuban american national foundation a washingtonbased think tank 
and lobby 
the foundation supported by the cuban american business elite 
has had wide influence on american policy the creation of radio 
marti and tv marti governmentsponsored broadcasts to cuba the 
lifting of the ban on aid to rebels fighting cuban troops in angola 
now convinced that communist cuba is in its declining days mas 
has turned the attention of his foundation to the future of a 
democratic cuba he discounts the complaints of critics who say he 
is power hungry and premature 
when castro is deposed he said the only presidency he expects 
to hold is that of his business and planning for postcastro cuba 
is important 
the future of cuba must be the result of serious 
wellconceived widely discussed plans with the leading experts of 
the world in each field said mas after all we can afford it 
we have the resources and the time 
work commissioned on behalf of the foundation including a 
constitution and economic plan for a hypothetical cuban government 
is to assist in the islands eventual rebuilding not to promote 
himself mas said in a recent interview 
mas said he has enlisted economists milton friedman and arthur 
laffer along with other experts to develop plans that would be 
handed over to a transitional postcastro government 
laffer is drawing up a list of fortune 500 companies willing to 
invest in a free cuba enough support could be generated through 
the private sector and the international bond market so that little 
us aid would be needed mas said 
the exiles for the most part expect that south florida would 
virtually become an extension of havana and vice versa 
mas estimates that each of the 2 million exiles would invest at 
least 3000 in cuba a total contribution of some 6 billion 
exiles also would lobby for the us government to open up its 
market to cuban goods as another way of stimulating development on 
the island he said 
the german miracle is going to be nothing compared to this 
cuban miracle said mas who also was appointed by gov bob 
martinez to chair a free cuba commission looking at the social and 
economic impact castros prospective overthrow would have on the 
