its kind of arrogant and presumptuous on the part of people 
here in miami basking under the florida sun and having worked in 
the last 30 years under the most democratic market economy in the 
globe to say this is how were going to handle a change in 
cuba said raul masvidal a foundation cofounder who quit in 
1985 
furthermore masvidal finds it hard to believe a transitional 
cuban government would be comfortable taking advice from people 
who represent the extreme right of the exile community 
jaime suchlicki director of the university of miamis institute 
of interamerican studies says theres no evidence castro is 
about to collapse so i think its somewhat premature although 
theres no harm done in preparing and looking at the options 
but masvidal does see some harm in it 
of course i would like to see mr castro killed tomorrow and 
thrown out of there but i dont think its about to happen and i 
think its very painful to be playing with the sensitivities of 
families and 11 million cuban people suffering every day from a 
severe form of repression he said 
mas said his critics simply are jealous of his success his 
company church and tower of florida specializes in laying 
telephone cable for southern bell it has made him a millionaire 
at the same time he built the foundation into a powerful force 
its more than 50 directors each pay 10000 a year to serve 
in that highprofile position however mas attracts 
controversy when ernesto betancourt former director of radio 
