<TEXT>
cancer robbed richard larmore 
of his ability to work and then it took his left leg 
that was aug 7 the seventh month since his application for 
disability aid began wending its way through the federal paperwork 
labyrinth and four months before he finally won approval 
critics say too many cases of deserving americans take too long 
to be decided by the social security disability system 
larmore 49 was seeking medicaid health insurance and a 44910 
monthly disability check from the social security administration to 
replace lost earnings from his former work as a plumbing and 
heating man 
while waiting for approval he survived on canned goods from a 
shelter for the homeless paid his rent on 4950 a week from the 
vermont department of social welfare and wondered how he would 
meet nearly 30000 in medical bills 
at times larmore said he gave serious thought to suicide 
i thought i had about as much chance of any dream coming true 
as a snowball in hell he said 
thanks to the advocacy of a community action agency worker and a 
vermont legal aid lawyer he got the benefits on his third appeal 
11 months later 
those familiar with the system say it can take years 
you can get justice in the system as long as youve got two 
years to devote to it said ted allen the vermont official 
responsible for a state agency that processes social security 
claims under federal contract 
anyone who really wants disability benefits should continue 
to appeal and they should get a lawyer allen said 
the disability system is complex the nearly 15 million people 
a year who apply for benefits under two disability programs go 
first to a statelevel office that reviews claims under contract 
with the federal government if the applicant is denied there 
twice he or she can pursue an appeal on two levels in the social 
security administration before resorting to the federal courts 
frank batestelli a spokesman at the social security 
administrations headquarters in baltimore said the nationwide 
average for processing disability claims on initial application 
runs from about 2 to three months 
those denied can ask the state office for reconsideration 
batestelli said he had no figures on the average length for that 
stage the average for review at the administrative law judge level 
is 205 days he said 
its not uncommon for it to take more than a year from the 
initial application to a ruling by the administrative law judge he 
said 
overall batestelli said more than twothirds of disability 
applicants are turned down on their initial application more than 
250000 appeals a year go to the administrative law judge level 
where statelevel rejections are reversed about 60 percent of the 
time he said 
critics say those reversals show the regulations set for 
statelevel reviewers are too tight 
those successful in winning help from the system get a base 
federal benefit of less than 400 a month plus an additional 
amount that varies depending on other sources of income the amount 
of working time the applicant spent paying into the social security 
system and the number of dependents 
the fundamental question asked by disability reviewers is 
whether the person asking for benefits can continue working despite 
his or her medical complaints 
the general accounting office the investigative arm of 
congress found in a study released last november that 58 percent 
of those people denied benefits in 1984 and still not receiving 
them three years later were not working that groups median family 
income was about 6500 in 1986 the gao said 
legal aid lawyers and other advocates for the disabled argue 
that the gao figures coupled with the number of reversals on 
appeal show the disability system is missing many of the people it 
should be serving and they say that is due to a bias built into a 
system that is trying to pinch federal pennies 
some social security administrative law judges who review 
disability cases appealed from statelevel reviewers complained 
last year to a us house subcommittee that they were being 
pressured to deny people benefits 
we have gotten allegations from administrative law judges of 
coercion threatened transfers and other kinds of pressures said 
rep barney frank dmass 
federal judges have criticized the agency saying it doesnt 
apply a courts ruling in one case to other similar cases 
district and circuit court rulings abound with references to social 
security systematically denying disability benefits to people 
entitled to them 
an agency memo cited in a disability case before a federal court 
in new york issued this order to statelevel reviewers do not 
apply a courts decision on one case to other cases if the 
administration decides to adopt the decision for other claims 
revised instructions will be issued 
among the most bitter and longrunning legal squabbles involving 
the disability system is that courts have repeatedly ruled that 
substantial weight must be given to the views of doctors who have 
treated a person for years when that person applies for disability 
benefits 
but lawyers with vermont legal aid and their counterpart 
agencies in other states say the treating physician rule is 
routinely ignored when applications are reviewed at the state level 
vermont officials say they are compelled to follow social 
security regulations even when they disagree with those rules 
allen the state disability aid official said he sees the 
problems resulting less from concerted federal policy than from 
simple bureaucratic unresponsiveness 
ive always thought of the social security administration as a 
brontosaurus with a real long spinal chord and slowacting 
neurons so that it steps on you not out of malice but because it 
didnt know you were there allen said 
by the time it realizes you were there he said youre a 
grease spot 
</TEXT>
