<TEXT>
an impressively orchestrated series of receptions speeches 
awards concerts dinners and other social events usually 
characterize national conventions of the greek orthodox church in 
the americas 
but this time something different is in the offing and it may 
jar the customarily graceful protocol 
a recently organized group of lay members plans to challenge 
operations of the churchs biennial layclergy congress july 912 
in washington demanding more representative participation 
the laity has been pretty much regulated controlled and 
stifled and authority has become more centralized said george d 
karcazes a chicago attorney and president of orthodox christian 
laity 
we want to restore the participatory process in the tradition 
of our faith 
such democraticstyle procedures in which both clergy and laity 
take part in church decisionmaking including the choosing of 
bishops is part of the eastern orthodox heritage 
but the lay organization says that policy has been eroded in the 
orderly running of the 2 millionmember us church 
unlike the roman catholic systen orthodoxy has a long 
tradition way back from the beginning of the church of lay 
participation and democratic processes karcazes said in an 
interview 
but that has been eliminated the laity has become totally 
subservient and blind followers its a trend over the past years 
with everincreasing centralization and less lay participation 
we want to energize the laity into more responsibile 
involvement its a necessary role were not doing something 
against the interest of the church but are coming to its aid 
he said the complaint is not aimed at archbishop iakovos the 
widely esteemed head of the church for 30 years but is a matter of 
revising representative methods and spurring the laity into 
rightful responsibilities 
we love and respect him as our spiritual leader and hes 
largely in agreement with what weve proposed karcazes said of 
the archbishop hes a charismatic individual with an 
international reputation 
but he would get more objective advice if he had elected laity 
around him instead of a mostly appointed council 
iakovos asked his view of the lay group said the movement 
may have some merit he has met with its leaders and said he 
supported possible steps to improve our system 
he suggested that instead of a separate organization the 
group may accept assignment of questions it has raised to a special 
church task force he quoted st pauls advice to do everything in 
orderly manner 
the group is proposing that the layclergy congress be comprised 
of diocesan bishops and clergy and lay representatives of the 555 
parishes each bishop and lay and clergy representative having one 
vote 
at present karcazes said the regulations also allow retired and 
auxiliary bishops to vote and also members of the archdiocesan 
council whose 118 lay members are appointed by the archbishop but 
automatically have votes 
the proposal says lack of any limit on the councils size could 
permit the congress of more than 1000 delegates to be stacked 
with appointees thereby diluting the process 
another proposed change would provide that the congress elect 
its presiding officer and secretary rather than the archbishop or 
his appointee presiding and his appointing the secretary as at 
present 
the laity organization also criticizes the large amount of time 
the congress devotes to ceremonial and social events and the 
little time given to critical issues confronting the church 
work sessions have been sandwiched between these often 
irrelevant events and sometimes cancelled the lay group says 
it says that tendency may be even greater this time because of 
the presence of ecumenical patriarch dimitrios i spiritual leader 
of all the worlds eastern orthodox christians 
he is spending most of july visiting in this country 
karcazes whose lay group sent the patriarch a welcoming message 
asking for a meeting with him said the group has more than 2000 
members in 35 states and was started because of wide grassroots 
concern 
were not a group of renegades but of thoughtful involved 
members of the church he said were simply giving voice to 
what many priests and prominent lay people have been saying and 
writing about for years 
he emphasized that the group does not question church teachings 
or the authority of bishops over doctrine and liturgy but wants 
more representative decisionmaking on other matters 
the channels exist on paper for it but are not functioning 
he said adding that the layclergy congress has become largely a 
spectacle of banquets political speakers ceremonies and other 
extraneous events 
its no longer a working deliberative conference where clergy 
and laity have time enough to sit down and seriously confront the 
issues facing the church today 
