<TEXT>
one of six education goals agreed on by 
president bush and the nations governors was to conquer illiteracy 
and boost workplace skills by the year 2000 the following report 
the third of an occasional series on those goals shows that even a 
potato chip company can no longer afford to ignore the issue 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
at first glance or crunch making the 
better potato chip might seem a pretty lowtech pursuit 
mary jones a potato inspector at the fritolay plant here for 
25 years knows otherwise 
when i first started it didnt take much to do this she 
said shouting above the 90decibel din of conveyors and frying 
machines as she weeded out green or flawed spuds now youve got 
to know something 
such as how to read and interpret computergenerated graphs 
showing whether chips are just the right thickness down to 
11000th of an inch 
or which delicate adjustments to recommend if chips are cooking 
too brown too spicy or with the wrong moisture content or how to 
ensure that each of 36 million bags of potato chips corn chips 
tortilla chips and cheese puffs made per week weighs precisely the 
right amount 
wrong decisions left uncorrected can lessen profits lose 
market share and not least create unhappy customers 
whether the product is the perfect potato chip or computer chip 
us employers of every stripe are finding daily reasons to worry 
about the workplace skills of both new and veteran employees 
nearly two years ago fritolay established a basic skills 
program for employees like jones employees who typify the 
workplace literacy crisis that afflicts the nation according 
to study after study 
jones 49 completed high school decades ago she can read and 
write she is not illiterate 
but like many other us workers she found she lacked the 
math computer and communication skills needed to thrive in an 
increasingly complicated and computerized workplace circumstances 
that were spotlighted in february when the bush administration and 
the nations governors set six goals to address americas education 
problems 
among them was a vow to make every adult american literate by 
the year 2000 and give all workers the opportunity to acquire 
the knowledge and skills from basic to highly technical needed to 
adapt to emerging new technologies work methods and markets 
us companies already spend some 30 billion a year on worker 
training a recent report by the national center on education and 
the economy estimated 
companies like eastman kodak polaroid and ibm have had 
stateoftheart workplace training programs for years virtually 
all states run workplace literacy programs pennsylvania for 
example is working with local unions to help commercial drivers 
pass stiffer licensing exams 
yet some experts worry that the nations workplace literacy 
efforts are misguided too often such programs focus on boosting 
basic reading or math skills but neglect issues like computer 
literacy how to commmunicate effectively with fellow workers how 
to type skimread or interpret complicated written or oral 
instructions 
whats happening now is that a phenomenal amount of money is 
being spent and much being wasted workers have been out of school 
for years but need to be trained for changes in the workplace 
said lawrence mikulecky a professor of language education at 
indiana university who has written extensively about workplace 
literacy 
the most effective programs relate basic skills with job 
training he said 
at a class this spring at fritolays orlando plant workers 
counted the number of big medium and small potato chips in several 
bags and graphed the results a simultaneous lesson in basic math 
and quality control 
plant managers plan to expand the program this summer to include 
courses in stress management presentation skills teamwork and 
problemsolving 
five years ago we werent doing anything said robert 
beeby chairman of fritolay now he said five of the companys 
38 plants have educational programs and more are being considered 
our whole style at fritolay is pushing down responsibility 
we dont want to have to tell our workers what to do beeby said 
literacy skills arent the big problem but dealing with the 
technology 
some companies might be motivated by foreign competition from 
japan or elsewhere the orlando plants worries are just 400 miles 
away in suburban atlanta said plant manager dave nicholson 
the plant opened in may 1965 only recently began to acquire 
the hightech machinery and computers that many newer fritolay 
facilities have 
one such plant in perry ga has stateoftheart equipment and 
a highly literate workforce when nicholson and other orlando 
employees visited the perry facility it crossed their minds that 
it might someday bite into the orlando plants market area which 
includes northern florida 
as the orlando plant modernized managers decided to assess the 
reading skills of its approximately 250 employees of the 70 
percent who voluntarily took the assessment about onethird were 
told by letter they could benefit from the skills program 
the plant began classes in september 1988 with the help of the 
orange county public schools the district supplied teachers and 
worked with managers to create curricula relating basic skills to 
making potato chips 
some 65 employees have participated in classes thus far 
workers take classes in a small room at the plant two hours a 
week for nine to 12 weeks half on company time half on their own 
they also can come in on their own from 7 am to 9 am on fridays 
to bone up on math and other skills using any one of a dozen 
computers in the classroom 
an initial challenge was ridding workers of the fear that 
managers were using the skills program to lay off weak readers 
at first i was worried said ruby jefferson a packer for 18 
years who has taken three of the workplace courses i dont have 
the fear i had before a lot of people here didnt get into the 
classes because of that im encouraging them to do it 
others had to be convinced that lessons would not be of the 
dick and jane variety said training manager donna badiedietz 
readings include the employee benefits package for example a 
writing lesson might include drawing up a maintenance work order 
the program isnt about boosting standardized reading scores 
managers insisted the aim is improved morale and an ability to 
carry out correct decisions in complex situations without having a 
manager looking over workers shoulders 
we have not set any sort of benchmark beeby said we 
could easily have said there is a portion of our workforce that 
hasnt graduated high school and lets replace them what we said 
instead was lets not cast those folks aside 
for many there also have been payoffs outside the plant 
my boys know more about this stuff than i do said bj 
parker a packer at the plant for 16 years who was practicing math 
on a computer i want to catch up with them 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
lee mitgang has covered education for the ap 
since 1981 
