<DOCNO> AP900703-0207 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
most of the nations five options trading 
exchanges say they will comply with federal securities regulators 
request for another delay in plans to list stock options on more 
than one exchange 
it was the second delay requested by the securities and exchange 
commission which last january asked the exchanges to voluntarilly 
hold off on multiple listings until june 30 
a stock option is a contract giving the right but not the 
obligation to buy or sell a certain security at a specified price 
by a certain date options are traded on stocks listed on exchanges 
or traded overthecounter via computer 
unlike stocks options provide no voting rights in running a 
company or dividends only the potential to profit from the 
stocks price movement 
traditionally an option could be listed at only one exchange 
but under multiple listing all the options exchanges could deal in 
any option 
in a letter to the five options exchanges sec chairman richard 
c breeden asked them to hold off until oct 1 on listing options 
that are already being traded on another exchange 
the sec hopes the exchanges can come up with a joint plan for 
linking the exchanges electronically by sept 21 breeden said 
last week breeden said the sec has the authority by law to 
order the exchanges to accept any linkage system but the agency 
prefers to have the exchanges develop the system 
the june 29 letter to the heads of the chicago board of options 
exchange and the american new york pacific and philadelphia stock 
exchanges was disclosed monday by the sec 
officials at the philadelphia american new york and pacific 
stock exchanges said they would honor breedens request 
but the chicago board of options said it would be 
inappropriate to comment publicly before informing the sec of 
its stance 
until january most options on stocks listed on an exchange were 
traded exclusively in one marketplace the privelege for trading a 
specific option was assigned to an exchange by lottery a system 
the exchanges favored but the sec felt was uncompetitive 
but a rule passed by the sec last year to ensure customers would 
get the best possible price abolished the limitations on multiple 
trading of options all new options those listed for trading after 
january can be traded on any options exchange 
last week breeden said a system linking the exchanges was 
feasible and that four of the five exchanges had agreed to operate 
a system called pipe for public investor privileged express the 
philadelphia stock exchange supports a different system the 
auction intermarket system which is similar in most instances but 
has the added factor of time priority 
if more than one exchange shows the same price for an option 
the philadelphia system would send the order to the exchange that 
posted that price first the pipe version would allow the exchange 
where the order was first directed to match that price 
weve suggested a compromise to the other exchanges and the 
sec said nicholas giordano president of the philadelphia 
exchange 
under the plan the pipe system could be used as long as it 
lists only post jan 22 stock options and can evolve into a 
timeprice system 
giordano said that if pipe turns out to be more competitive than 
the auction intermarket system the philadelphia excahange will go 
along with the others 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

