<DOCNO> AP900703-0250 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
it began as a secret project to create an 
affordable durable subcompact with 60milepergallon efficiency 
that would leapfrog the japanese and vault the nations biggest 
automaker into the 1990s and beyond 
eight years later general motors corps saturn has transmuted 
into a significantly larger pricier car with a lower mileage 
rating a less ambitious production schedule and an audience of 
skeptics 
gms showcase saturn project has in many respects become a test 
of whether american industry can adapt and beat the makers of 
hondas and toyotas at what they do best luring american consumers 
just how gm intends to convince the buying public that saturn is 
superior remains to be seen 
gm chairman roger smith saturns most enthusiastic supporter 
has said he plans to be at the wheel of the premiere model when it 
rolls off the assembly line at the saturn complex in spring hill 
tenn later this summer 
but gm officials have declined to specify a date for the worlds 
first good look at a massproduced saturn or whether they even 
plan a rollout ceremony models are supposed to arrive in dealer 
showrooms by fall 
the saturn saga began in june 1982 when gm put its best brains 
to work on a hushhush project aimed at revolutionizing carmaking 
in the united states they codenamed it saturn after the us 
rocket that helped overcome the soviet lead in space exploration 
about 2 years later smith formally established saturn corp 
calling it the key to gms longterm competitivness survival and 
success 
since then curiosity and publicity have been diluted by 
impatience cynicism setbacks and design alterations the 60 mpg 
6000 subcompact prototype wonder that smith flaunted became a 35 
mpg 10000 compact with no obvious advantages over foreign rivals 
gms initial investment of 5 billion shrank to 3 billion it 
halved the number of workers to 3000 and the annual production 
from 500000 to 250000 
there also have been suggestions of infighting between gm 
executives and their subordinates at saturn who originally were 
given wide latitude to move more quickly and responsively than at 
their fat lumbering parent in detroit 
nonetheless the goal has remained basically unchanged build 
and sell a car that can recapture a market gm has lost to its 
competitors mainly the fiercely efficient japanese 
its a lot more than just another 250000 units said joseph 
phillippi who follows the automotive industry for shearson lehman 
hutton inc the new york investment firm its the whole 
process the completely integrated manufacturing nature 
saturns underlying premise is a clean sheet approach to 
carmaking nothing in gms manufacturing past was required for use 
in saturn design and engineering approaches for the car were to be 
all new 
if successful the saturn project holds tremendous potential for 
the us auto industry 
one of detroits main frustrations which saturn presumably will 
overcome is the lengthy time it takes to bring a new car to 
market especially when consumer tastes can shift rapidly japan is 
seen as the leader in what the industry calls quick product 
turnaround time usually three years or less 
some saturn critics have said quick turnaround is exactly what 
saturn lacks its taken eight years to produce a threeyear car 
but saturn president richard g lefauve has said that time was 
needed to be sure the car was right for importconscious buyers 
we had to make constant adjustments to make the car more 
responsive he said most people think of it as a domestic 
product this car is not really a domestic in that it is not 
designed in a domestic sense 
the saturn complex that now occupies the rolling horsefarm 
country of tennessee is an experiment in automotive 
selfsufficiency the plant has its own stamping plants powertrain 
assembly and foundries 
but perhaps the most farreaching innovation is saturns labor 
agreement with the united auto workers union workers are organized 
into teams with broad decisionmaking powers and responsibilities 
they receive hundreds of hours of training and are expected to 
understand the economics behind each car 
it leapfrogs the japanese structure and the european 
structure said mike bennett president of saturns uaw local 
1853 if there is a new direction for the uaw its in spring 
hill tennessee 
saturns factory laborers come from gm plants or layoff lists in 
32 states and 136 gm locations but they are working under a 
contract that their 500000 fellow autoworker unionists would find 
alien the chief differences 
the contract has no specific expiration date exactly one year 
from the date of job 1 management and labor may begin modifying 
the contract if necessary on a daybyday basis 
saturn workers have a hand in design of the vehicle and the 
factory itself 
job classifications which number in the dozens in traditional 
automobile factories have been pared to a few 
saturn workers get paid 80 percent of the wages other uaw 
members receive but are eligible for bonuses depending on the 
cars success 
elements of the contract could spread to other auto plants if 
saturn proves successful 
if we see other plants adopt less job classification 
categories that would be a mark of success said automotive 
analyst scott merlis of morgan stanley amp co in new york 
gms most immediate concerns are whether saturn sells and who 
buys it 
the cars current estimated price hurls it against some of the 
toughest competition in the us car market in which gm will not 
only be battling with other automakers but itself as well gms 
most popular models the fourdoor chevrolet corsica and twodoor 
beretta are in the same price range 
that means gm must attract the import buyer the company has 
said it hopes 80 percent of saturn buyers will be import owners 
the bottom line is that if you are driving a honda or toyota 
corolla today you are going to feel very comfortable in a saturn 
car lefauve says if youre driving a chevrolet cavalier or 
something else in that area you arent going to feel that 
comfortable 
but many automotive analysts remain skeptical about saturns 
ability to change an entrenched preference for imports gms 
passenger car market share has shrunk from about 44 percent to 33 
percent just in the time since the saturn project was conceived 
while the japanese share has risen from 19 percent to about 25 
percent 
moreover industry studies continually show a growing american 
preference for the reliability of japanese cars just this past 
week for example jd power and associates a respected industry 
research firm said its study of 1990 buyers found that owners of 
japanese models were the happiest 
david healy who follows the auto industry for barclays bank in 
new york said he would consider saturn successful if it were able 
to derive less than half its market from wouldbe buyers of other 
gm cars 
otherwise healy said saturn may be an artistic success and a 
financial failure 
</TEXT>
