<DOCNO> AP900703-0251 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
over the past 25 years john cunniff has written 
more than 5000 columns and interviewed hundreds of business and 
financial newsmakers in his role as ap business analyst in an 
occasional series he revisits some of the people whose 
oldfashioned wisdom has withstood the test of time 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
thomas ohara was a good student at wayne state 
university but he didnt graduate near the top of his class which 
meant he was lucky to land an accountants job at 15 a week 
those were the gray days of 1936 in the midst of the great 
depression and just before the great war a time when communism 
seemed on the way up and american spirits on the way down 
oharas spirits didnt succumb better red than dead was a 
common slogan at the time but it made no sense to him my goal 
was to catch the fast movers the guys making 18 a week he said 
fred russell a young fellow with little cash and big hopes 
provided the opportunity an investment club to be guided by george 
nicholson jr a stockbroker not long out of harvard business 
school 
russells hope was that each member would invest 10 a month and 
that the total would be invested in stocks it was 1940 
fifty 50 years later ohara and his wife eleanor were among two 
dozen kitchentable investors who gathered earlier this year to 
dine on filet mignon and celebrate the golden anniversary of the 
mutual investment club of detroit 
in the 600 months since 1940 club members have invested 
227877 their joint portfolio now is worth 180125592 
that appreciation is even more dramatic considering club member 
withdrawals over the years more than 1 million to finance 
businesses homes college educations travel retirement 
the story of the mutual investment club reflected in the 
fruitful lives of ohara and his coinvestors is a lesson in the 
wisdom of oldfashioned thrift which fell far out of fashion in 
the booming 1980s 
the investment club is a mix of old and young don danko 
president is 43 bob bilke a mere 28 and ken janke jr just 32 
oharas two sons are members too in contrast 10 of the 22 
members are 70 or older 
the combination works well if youth has dreams age has 
experience where younger members sparkle with hope older ones 
glow with knowledge they complement each other 
the detroit club became the nucleus of the national association 
of investors corp of which ohara is chairman and ken janke sr 
president based in royal oak mich it has 126000 members 
14631 as individuals the rest in 6933 clubs 
most follow simple rules members make small monthly 
contributions usually between 10 and 50 and they reinvest all 
dividends withdrawals are allowed if contributions continue 
nicholson 83 now revered as the founding father of the 
international investment club movement laid down the rules back in 
1940 
invest regularly usually each month 
reinvest all dividends 
invest in growth companies those growing faster than their 
industries and the general economy 
other principles were developed diversifying because stocks 
ripen at varying times and biological testing to determine 
whether management is young enough to maintain performance for at 
least five years 
club members propose stocks for study and after the reports are 
in they vote typically shares are assigned to members on the 
basis of their total contributions and each month the share values 
are determined 
underlying the investment clubs way of doing things is the 
conviction that economic fluctuations the kind that cause so much 
excitement on wall street are of little concern to longterm 
investors on main street 
americas growth is strong they reason and when all the ups 
and downs are averaged out the arrow still points up when markets 
are up club assets rise when markets are down the same amount of 
money buys more shares 
investors who try to outguess the market arent likely to win 
says ohara a quiet man whose logic speaks profoundly he puts it 
this way 
the stock market is not important its the businesses the 
business effort might not be reflected in the stock market 
immediately but eventually it will 
look at individual companies and have confidence the market 
will recognize value it always has 
most of the time the gains are more steady than spectacular but 
sometimes a stock takes off 
the detroit club bought american cement later to become amcord 
at about 275 a share and sold six years later at 32 with the 
proceeds it bought kennecott copper at 25 and sold two years later 
at about 63 
more recently the club has become a large holder in american 
family an insurer selling now at more than 15 a share the clubs 
average acquisition price was about 1 a share 
soon after joining the detroit club ohara was drafted and sent 
to iceland with little to buy he doubled his contributions to 20 
a month and continued to do so throughout the war 
russell rejected for service by a heart condition invested the 
money of ohara and other members by the end of 1946 the record 
read contributions 5080 withdrawals 2519 holdings 15354 
not bad for wartime and the notsocertain prospects for the 
postwar period 
more 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP900703-0252 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
after a slump the value rose to 33222 by 1952 despite 
withdrawals the value nearly doubled again by 1955 once more by 
the end of the decade and again in 1965 when it reached 246738 
by the end of 1969 after deposits of 75327 over the years 
the portfolio was worth 535604 a critical mass had been 
assembled the dividends always reinvested now totaled more each 
year than member contributions 
bad times severely tested the clubs philosophy early in the 
1970s however brokers went broke investors lost fortunes and 
many clubs like detroits disbanded inflation raged 
keeping the faith detroit club members maintained 
contributions at a rate exceeding 7000 a year even so their 
portfolio suffered its value fell more than 140000 from the 1969 
peak to just 393434 a year later after recovering to 430000 in 
the next three years it fell again to 387959 in 1974 the club 
still bought confident of a rise to come it did 
by 1979 the portfolio was valued at 759038 and by the end of 
1982 when the market rediscovered fundamentally sound stocks it 
topped 1 million for the first time of course it continued to 
grow 
over 50 years oharas monthly contributions amounted to a 
total of only 12000 the club records show he withdrew 186000 
over the years but that he still had 183000 left in the portfolio 
considering the small sum invested a person might have saved 
that amount by foregoing cigarettes the return seemed bountiful 
it didnt make millionaires of everyone but did allow them to 
realize some dreams 
a 3000 withdrawal in 1950 helped russell buy a howard johnson 
restaurant franchise eventually he owned three along with other 
food outlets and left his widow a comfortable inheritance 
bob burger who joined in 1946 withdrew 5000 years ago to 
found a business that developed into chemetco a miniconglomerate 
john biscomb indulged an intense interest in william 
shakespeare went to england and studied the bard on his own 
grounds in avon and london 
norman hill an original and wily investor allowed his 
contributions to accumulate to a current 346000 a pillow of 
comfort in his retirement 
ohara and his wife traveled widely bought their dream house 
sent their sons to private schools and colleges and convinced them 
to buy into the club ohara became a new york stock exchange 
governor and still serves as a consultant on issues affecting 
individual investors 
persistence is both the secret and the scourge of club investors 
the hardest thing is just to stay in the business ohara 
said in bad times its easy to quit 
with dedication compounding works wonders although it isnt 
easy to explain this to those of a modern getrichquick mentality 
begin with a penny and double its value each day and 10 days 
later it still amounts to only 5 but keep doubling and you have 
5 million in about a month 
the detroit club amassed its fortune at a modest annualized rate 
of 122 percent doubling its assets each five to six years 
can the detroit experience be repeated in these times of instant 
gratification yes if you have the motivation and the patience 
club members say 
modest goals help remember half a century ago oharas goal 
was simply to offset the 3 a week shortfall in his paycheck 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

