<DOCNO> AP900703-0253 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the story of the mutual investment club of 
detroit is a textbook example of the wisdom of investing for the 
long term 
below at a glance are some facts about the club and commentary 
from ap business analyst john cunniff who first reported on the 
club in the 1960s 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
origin the club was organized in 1940 when some young men 
tried to put the great depression behind them and concentrate on 
better times 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
leadership fred russell a fellow with little cash but big 
hopes had the idea for a club to invest in stocks george 
nicholson a young broker drew up the guidelines becoming widely 
recognized as the father of the investment club movement thomas 
ohara a young accountant made investment clubs his career 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
guiding principles invest small amounts regularly usually each 
month reinvest all dividends invest in growth companies those 
growing faster than their industries and the general economy 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
membership as the detroit club succeeded after world war ii it 
gave birth to the national association of investors corp which 
now has 126000 members 14631 as individuals the rest in 6933 
clubs 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
portfolio growth 10 and 20 investments built assets worth 
millions 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
sample investment the goal was to double the investment within 
five years but sometimes the results were better for example the 
purchase of american cement at 275 a share and its sale six years 
later for about 32 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
withdrawals more than 1 million was withdrawn over the years 
to buy houses finance businesses pay tuitions provide 
retirements 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
commentary there are many messages in the mutual clubs 
experience 
have patience recognize that time is a silent ingredient as 
important to a portfolio as yeast is to bread 
do your homework know your investments invest in individual 
stocks not in the market 
invest for the long term dont try to time trade or outguess 
the market and forget about trying to fathom the shortterm ups 
and downs of the economic cycle 
recognize that down markets are temporary to be followed 
by better times 
be confident that americas economy continues to grow even if 
it develops a cold from time to time 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP900703-0254 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
here are some facts and figures about general 
motors corps saturn corp and its products 
headquarters troy mich about 15 miles north of detroit 
factory complex on 2400 acres in spring hill tenn 35 miles 
south of nashville about 44 million square feet onsite 
facilities to manufacture engines transmissions and components 
which frequently are made elsewhere and shipped to an assembly 
plant paint and final assembly operations also are on site 
cost about 3 billion twothirds of it at the factory 
employment about 3000 at full production 
management richard g lefauve president 
union united auto workers local 1853 mike bennett president 
vehicle likely to be two and fourdoor versions at the start 
with a hatchback station wagon in the future conventional and 
multivalve engines and standard and automatic transmissions will 
be available 
production target about 250000 units annually by the end of 
1991 
market saturns principle market is likely import car buyers 
base price 10000 to 12000 
dealers a network of dealerships separate from gm franchises 
nationwide the first cars will be available this fall in the 
southeast and california 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

