<TEXT>
foreign ministers from 24 
industrialized nations meet wednesday to discuss extending their 
aid program for poland and hungary to four other new democracies in 
central europe 
on the ministers agenda is a recommendation from the european 
communitys executive commission to include bulgaria 
czechoslovakia east germany and yugoslavia in the yearold aid 
program 
the program known by its french initials as phare would supply 
food aid provide training and financial assistance help clean up 
the environment and contribute to economic reconstruction and 
investments 
the four countries have asked to be included in the program 
which has already raised 310 million for poland and hungary an 
additional 62 million is due to be committed by the end of this 
year and diplomats said another 248 million has already been 
earmarked for bulgaria czechoslovakia east germany and yugoslavia 
the ec leaders delayed making a final decision to give financial 
or other help to the soviet union at their june 2526 summit in 
dublin ireland they have agreed in principle to support president 
mikhail gorbachevs attempts at economic reform by giving him some 
kind of assistance 
aid to the kremlin will likely be debated at this weeks summit 
in london of the leaders of the 16 nations of the north atlantic 
treaty organization and also next week at the economic sumit of the 
seven largest industrialized nations in houston texas 
the ministers originally included romania in their 
recommendation but then dropped it from the list because of concern 
over political developments there notably the government crackdown 
on civilian demonstrators in june 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

